To derive any string the start symbol S must take one of its two rules:

1. S → NT41 NT23  
2. S → NT41 NT58

Consequently, the very first token of every generated string must be the first token produced by NT41.

The only productions for NT41 are  
 NT41 → NT34 NT49 → 't26' 't57'  
 NT41 → 't13'

Hence NT41 can start a derivation only with ‘t13’ (single token) or with the two-token sequence ‘t26 t57’.  
The given string begins with the token ‘t28’, which is neither ‘t13’ nor ‘t26’. Therefore no derivation from S can match the first token of the supplied string, so the grammar cannot generate it.

No

The start symbol S must begin its derivation with NT41 (S → NT41 NT23 or S → NT41 NT58).

NT41 can generate only
• 't13'  (via NT41 → 't13')
• 't26 t57' (via NT41 → NT34 NT49, NT34 → 't26', NT49 → 't57')

Hence every string in the language must start with either t13 or the pair t26 t57.

The given string begins with t58, so it cannot be produced by the grammar.

No
